<!-- REPAIR VS REPLACE — 50% rule -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07, Repair or Replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The 50% rule for washing machines</h2>
    <p class="lead">If a repair costs more than half of a comparable new machine, replacing usually makes more sense, but premium brands flip the math. Here's the rubric our technicians actually use on a service call.</p>

    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict repair">Almost always repair</span>
        <h3>Miele · Bosch · Speed Queen · Electrolux Professional · Asko</h3>
        <p>Built for 15-20+ year service lives. Replacement runs $1,800-$5,000. Even a $700 control board on a 12-year-old Miele W1 is the right call, the drum, bearings, motor, and suspension all have another decade in them.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Tub bearing replacement worth it through year 15-18</li>
          <li>Door gasket / shock absorbers always worth it</li>
          <li>Control board: yes, even at $500-$700</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card">
        <span class="rvr-verdict judge">Judgment call, use the 50% rule</span>
        <h3>Samsung · LG · Whirlpool · Maytag · GE · Frigidaire</h3>
        <p>Mid-market units have an honest 8-12 year design life. Past year 8, when one major component fails the others aren't far behind, fix the drain pump and the bearing fails 6 months later.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Under 8 years AND repair under $300 → repair</li>
          <li>Over 10 years AND repair over $400 → consider replacing</li>
          <li>Tub bearing failure on 8+ year unit → strongly consider replacing</li>
          <li>Multiple component failures in one visit → almost always replace</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

